# Title: Ledger Repair Primer (link+hash chain)
#------------------
This is a flattened version of repair_ledger_links that demonstrates
the flow and program logic. Context and implementation details can be found
below. While this is viable, flatten, python code, it does not
follow strict pyright/black/ruff/PEP8 standards. It is for demonstorative,
instructive and informational purposes.

# rows_desc: newest -> oldest, length N+1
rows_desc = fetch_desc(limit + 1)

# seed from the true predecessor (outside the window)
seed_prev_id   = rows_desc[limit]["id"] if len(rows_desc) > limit else None
seed_prev_hash = rows_desc[limit]["event_hash"] if len(rows_desc) > limit else None

# work on the N newest rows, oldest -> newest
window_rows = rows_desc[:limit][::-1]

updates = []
prev_id = seed_prev_id
prev_hash = seed_prev_hash

for row in window_rows:
    rid = row["id"]

    # current values (from DB)
    cur_prev_id = row.get("prev_event_id")
    cur_prev_hash = row.get("prev_hash")

    # what they SHOULD be
    new_prev_id = prev_id
    new_prev_hash = prev_hash

    # recompute hash using your canonical function
    tmp = {k: row.get(k) for k in _HASH_KEYS}
    tmp["prev_event_id"] = new_prev_id
    tmp["prev_hash"] = new_prev_hash
    new_event_hash = compute_event_hash(tmp)

    # record needed update
    if (
        cur_prev_id != new_prev_id
        or cur_prev_hash != new_prev_hash
        or row.get("event_hash") != new_event_hash
    ):
        updates.append((rid, new_prev_id, new_prev_hash, new_event_hash))

    # advance for next item
    prev_id = rid
    prev_hash = new_event_hash


* -----------------
* Ethos and Modality
* -----------------

Context
- The transactions_ledger is a singly linked list:
  prev_event_id -> previous row’s id
  prev_hash     -> previous row’s event_hash
  event_hash    -> hash(canonical payload INCLUDING prev_event_id/prev_hash)
- Writer must compute event_hash AFTER prev_* are set.
- Verifier/Repair must use the SAME compute_event_hash() as writer.

Canonical Fields (HASH_KEYS)
- id
- happened_at_utc (UTC-naive ISO micros)
- prev_event_id
- prev_hash
- type
- slice
- operation
- request_id
- actor_id
- target_id
- customer_id
- entity_ids_json
- changed_fields_json
- refs_json

Golden Rules
1) Always hash the final payload (with prev_* already set).
2) Always use compute_event_hash(...) from app.slices.transactions.services.
3) Define the chain head deterministically as the last row by (happened_at_utc DESC, id DESC).
4) Store happened_at_utc as UTC-naive; normalize consistently before hashing.

Repair Algorithm (windowed)
- Fetch the latest N+1 rows ORDER BY (happened_at_utc DESC, id DESC).
- Seed prev_* from the (N+1)th row (the TRUE predecessor outside the window):
    seed_prev_id   = rows_desc[N].id    (if exists; else None)
    seed_prev_hash = rows_desc[N].hash  (if exists; else None)
- Take the window of N newest rows and iterate OLDEST -> NEWEST.
- For each row:
    new_prev_id   = prior row’s id (or seed_prev_id for first)
    new_prev_hash = prior row’s event_hash (or seed_prev_hash for first)
    tmp = dict(row); tmp.prev_event_id = new_prev_id; tmp.prev_hash = new_prev_hash
    new_event_hash = compute_event_hash(tmp)
    If any of (prev_event_id, prev_hash, event_hash) differ from stored → plan update.
- Dry-run by default; apply only on explicit confirm.

Why N+1?
- Without the extra row, you’ll incorrectly anchor the OLDEST row in your window to None.
- The (N+1)th row provides the “true” predecessor hash; a healthy chain should produce zero updates.

Verification Algorithm
- Walk ALL rows in ASC order (or the same window seeded as above).
- For each row:
    recompute expected_hash via compute_event_hash(with corrected prev_*).
    Ensure:
      row.event_hash == expected_hash
      row.prev_event_id == prev_id (prior row’s id or None for very first)
      row.prev_hash == prev_hash (prior row’s event_hash or None for very first)

Common Pitfalls
- Hashing with a datetime object (serialize to ISO micros first).
- Different canonical fields between writer vs verifier vs repair.
- Anchoring repair to None instead of the real predecessor.
- Changing which JSON keys go into refs/changed_fields after deployment (allowed, but re-run repair to normalize historic rows to new canonicalization).
- Reusing request_id (idempotency will collapse events).

Operational Tips
- Pause emission during repair if you plan to write.
- Always snapshot DB before destructive ops.
- “Verify” in Admin UI should match this algorithm exactly.
- Keep HASH_KEYS and compute_event_hash() as the single source of truth—import them everywhere else.

Quick Commands
- Verify: PYTHONPATH=. python scripts/Python/verify_ledger_chain.py
- Repair (dry): PYTHONPATH=. python scripts/Python/repair_ledger_links.py --limit 200
- Repair (apply): PYTHONPATH=. python scripts/Python/repair_ledger_links.py --limit 200 --commit
